<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1435,389,450]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">
The two species of this group are characterized by the buttonlike projection at the apical margin of the last segment of the male antenna (
<figureCitation box="[386,493,425,450]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">Figs. 7, 8</figureCitation>
).
